In an operation that started earlier this week, the dry dock was flooded for the first time to allow the vessel to float.

It was then manoeuvred out of the dock in a three-hour operation this morning, and berthed at a nearby jetty.

Teams will now continue to fit out the ship and prepare the vessel for sea trials in 2016, and it will be fully operational by 2020.

However, there are continuing doubts over the military's ability to fill out the plane with its full contingent of F-35 Lightning fighter jets. The Queen Elizabeth is equipped to carry 36 of the planes, but so far only three of the 48 ordered from the U.S. manufacturers have arrived.

For the naming ceremony a fortnight ago a dummy version made from aluminium and fibreglass was displayed on top of the craft because no real ones were available to make the journey.

The Government has ordered 48 of the planes in total, and plans to buy more, but it is unclear when the deliveries will finally be made.

